\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Exercise 1:

\series default
 In the above letter,
 I have proven that the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=2x^{2}+2x-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=8x-1$
\end_inset

 are,
 respectively,
 continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 and at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 This is because the above work is a couple of epsilon-delta proofs with slightly different wording:
 We are given a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

,
 represented by the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

,
 and construct a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

,
 represented by the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

,
 that guarantees that,
 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-value within 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 (resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0.5$
\end_inset

),
 the resulting 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-value 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 (resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

) is within 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(1)$
\end_inset

 (resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g(0.5)$
\end_inset

).
